# Connecting to ADLSGen2/Blob Storage

## Creating Datastore for the Data source

Step â€“ 1: Open the Data tab under the Assets section in your workspace.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Step â€“ 2: Open the Datastores tab to create a new datastore for the data source.

- Add the URL to the Storage Account manually using the template provided or make use of the azure subscription to pick a storage account.
- Do not provide any credential.
- **Make sure to check the â€œUse workspace managed identity for data preview and profiling in Azure Machine Learning Studioâ€.**

Step â€“ 1: Open the Datasource once created and click on create data asset.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Step â€“ 2: Enter the path to the file that needs to be added as the data asset or browse the storage path for the same.

## Connecting to Workspace

**Note â€“ While making use of user-assigned managed identity, make sure no system-assigned managed identity is attached to the compute.**

Use the following code to connect to the workspace:

from azureml.core import Workspace

from azureml.core.authentication import MsiAuthentication

&nbsp;

\# msi_auth = MsiAuthentication() to use the computeâ€™s managed identity

msi_auth = MsiAuthentication(client_id = â€œ&lt;managed-identity-client-id&gt;â€)

ws = Workspace.from_config(auth = msi_auth)

- Make sure to provide the managed identity (system or user-assigned) the permission to access the data source.
  - Storage Blob Data Contributor: Read and Write access to the blob.
  - Storage Blob Data Reader: Read Only access to the blob.

Step â€“ 1: Go to your compute/ managed identity and copy its name.

Sample: For compute: &lt;Workspace-name&gt;/computes/&lt;Compute-name&gt; (Search under User, group, or service principle)

For managed identity: &lt;Managed-Identity-Name&gt; (Search under Managed Identity)

Step â€“ 2: Go to your data source, in the Access Control (IAM), in the role assignment add your managed identity with the required permission/s.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Reading from the Data Source

Use the following code to read a file from the data source:

from azureml.core import Datastore, Dataset

import pandas as pd

datastore_name = "&lt;datastore-name&gt;"

blob_datastore = Datastore.get(ws, datastore_name)

datastore_path = "&lt;path-to-file&gt;"

dataset = Dataset.Tabular.from_delimited_files((blob_datastore, datastore_path))

df=dataset.to_pandas_dataframe()

print(df.head())

Documentation: [TabularDatasetFactory class](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/python/api/azureml-core/azureml.data.dataset_factory.tabulardatasetfactory?view=azure-ml-py)

- &lt;datastore-name&gt;, enter the name of the datastore created for the data source in step 1
- &lt;path-to-file&gt;, enter the relative path (/azure/test-data.csv) to the file to be read in the data source.

Sample: Workspace - **APIM_WS_Demo**

Storage - **apimwsdemo7357579952** (Blob Storage)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure Sample Read from blob storage.

## Writing to the Data Source

Use the following code to write a file to the data source:

from azureml.core import Datastore, Dataset

import pandas as pd

datastore_name = "&lt;datastore-name&gt;"

blob_datastore = Datastore.get(ws, datastore_name)

datastore_path = "&lt;path-to-file&gt;"

dataset = Dataset.Tabular.from_delimited_files((blob_datastore, datastore_path))

df=dataset.to_pandas_dataframe()

datastore_path = "&lt;path-in-datastore&gt;"

\# data = \[\['A', 1\], \['B', 2\], \['C', 3\]\]

\# df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=\['X', 'Y'\])

\# Using the data imported in the previous step

new_data = df.head()

new_dataset = Dataset.Tabular.register_pandas_dataframe(new_data, (blob_datastore,datastore_path),"test-data")

print("Data written successfully to Blob Storage")

- The file will be stored at the path specified as &lt;path-in-datastore&gt;.
- Able to store only files in parquet format.

Sample: Workspace - **APIM_WS_Demo**

## Creating a job to Read and Write to the Data source

Use the following code to create a job to read and write to the data source:

from azure.ai.ml import command, Input, Output, MLClient

from azure.ai.ml.constants import AssetTypes, InputOutputModes

from azure.identity import DefaultAzureCredential, ManagedIdentityCredential

from azureml.core.workspace import Workspace

from azure.ai.ml.entities import ManagedIdentityConfiguration

subscription_id = "bc4b1f88-8243-46e8-a551-cfad428ca531"

resource_group = "shell-08-rg-Bijeshjoseph00000000"

workspace = "APIM_WS_Demo"

credential = DefaultAzureCredential()

ml_client = MLClient(credential, subscription_id, resource_group, workspace)

\# identity = ManagedIdentityConfiguration() to use compute's managed identity

identity = ManagedIdentityConfiguration(client_id="c7b51ff5-57c6-44ab-9581-b01affc84aa6")

input_path = "azureml://datastores/&lt;datastore-name&gt;/paths/&lt;path-to-input-file&gt;â€

output_path = "azureml://datastores/&lt;datastore-name&gt; /paths/demo/&lt;path-to-output-file&gt;â€"

data_type = AssetTypes.URI_FILE

input_mode = InputOutputModes.RO_MOUNT

output_mode = InputOutputModes.RW_MOUNT

\# Path in data source to read from

inputs = {

&nbsp;   "input_data": Input(type=data_type, path=input_path, mode=input_mode)

}

\# Path in data source to write to

outputs = {

&nbsp;   "output_data": Output(type=data_type,

&nbsp;                         path=output_path,

&nbsp;                         mode=output_mode,

&nbsp;                 )

}

\# Initiating a job to copy a file in the data source and save it in another directory within the data source

job = command(

&nbsp;   command="cp ${{inputs.input_data}} ${{outputs.output_data}}",

&nbsp;   inputs=inputs,

&nbsp;   outputs=outputs,

&nbsp;   environment="azureml://registries/azureml/environments/sklearn-1.1/versions/4",

&nbsp;   compute="&lt;compute instance/compute cluster -name&gt;",

&nbsp;   identity=identity

)

ml_client.jobs.create_or_update(job)

Sample: Workspace - **APIM_WS_Demo**

Storage - **apimwsdemo7357579952** (Blob Storage)

# Connecting to SQL Server

## Creating Datastore for the Data source

Step â€“ 1: Open the Data tab under the Assets section in your workspace.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Step â€“ 2: Open the Datastores tab to create a new datastore for the data source.

- Add the URL to the SQL server manually or make use of the azure subscription to pick a storage account.
- Do not provide any credential.
- **Make sure to check the â€œUse workspace managed identity for data preview and profiling in Azure Machine Learning Studioâ€.**

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure For SQL Server

- Azure ML v2 APIs, do not provide provision for creating data asset for SQL server.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure No option from SQL database

## Connecting to Workspace

**Note â€“ While making use of user-assigned managed identity, make sure no system-assigned managed identity is attached to the compute.**

Use the following code to connect to the workspace:

from azureml.core import Workspace

from azureml.core.authentication import MsiAuthentication

&nbsp;

\# msi_auth = MsiAuthentication() to use the computeâ€™s managed identity

msi_auth = MsiAuthentication(client_id = â€œ&lt;managed-identity-client-id&gt;â€)

ws = Workspace.from_config(auth = msi_auth)

- Make sure to provide the managed identity (system or user-assigned) the permission to access the database.
  - Grant Reader permission at the SQL Server level.
  - db_datareader: can read all data from all user tables and views.

## Reading from SQL Server

Step â€“ 1: Create a user with following the permissions in the SQL database:

CREATE USER \[&lt;name_of_managed_identity&gt;\] FROM EXTERNAL PROVIDER;

ALTER ROLE db_datareader ADD MEMBER \[&lt;name_of_managed_identity&gt;\];

\--SELECT \* FROM sysusers;  --to list all users for the database

Step â€“ 2: Use the following code to read from the SQL server:

from azureml.core import Datastore, Dataset

from azureml.data.datapath import DataPath

datastore_name = "&lt;datastore-name&gt;"

sql_datastore = Datastore.get(ws,datastore_name)

table_name = "&lt;table-name&gt;"

\# sql_query = f"SELECT \* FROM {table_name}"

sql_query = DataPath(sql_datastore, f'SELECT \* FROM {table_name}')

dataset = Dataset.Tabular.from_sql_query(sql_query,(sql_datastore,msi_auth))

\# dataset = Dataset.Tabular.from_sql_query(sql_query)

df = dataset.to_pandas_dataframe()

print(df.head())

## Writing to SQL Server

Write to SQL Server is not allowed using managed identity, need to make use of Service Principle for writing to SQL Servers.

The following code can be used to write to SQL database:

**Using SQL database username and password**

import pyodbc

from azureml.core import Workspace

from azureml.core.authentication import MsiAuthentication

msi_auth = MsiAuthentication()

workspace = Workspace.from_config(auth = msi_auth)

server = "&lt;server-name&gt;.database.windows.net"

database = "&lt;database-name&gt;"

username = "&lt;db-username&gt;"

password = "&lt;db-password&gt;"

driver = "{ODBC Driver 17 for SQL Server}"

conn_str = f"DRIVER={driver};SERVER={server};DATABASE={database};UID={username};PWD={password}"

\# data_to_insert = \[(1,"abc"),(2,"xyz"),(3,"efg")\] Sample data

table_name ="&lt;table-name&gt;"

with pyodbc.connect(conn_str) as conn:

&nbsp;   cursor = conn.cursor()

&nbsp;   for row in data_to_insert:

&nbsp;       cursor.execute("&lt;SQL Query&gt;")

&nbsp;       # cursor.execute(f"INSERT INTO {table_name} (SNo, test_data) VALUES (?,?)",row) Sample insert

&nbsp;   conn.commit()

Sample â€“ SQL Database - midemosqlserver/demoSQLdb

![](data:image/png;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure Sample Write to SQL Server

**Using SQL database username and password**

- Make sure to provide the service principal the permission to access the database.
  - Grant Reader permission at the SQL Server level.
  - db_datawriter: can add, delete, or change data in all user tables.
  - db_ddladmin: can run any Data Definition Language (DDL) command in a database.
